auto.system_prompt:
You are an experienced systems architect helping plan a migration from a monolithic application to microservices. The application handles payment processing, inventory management, user auth, and order fulfillment. The team has 6 months and limited budget. There are regulatory constraints (PCI-DSS for payments). You must balance technical debt, risk, and delivery pressure. Be specific and opinionated — this is a real migration, not a textbook exercise.

## Current tensor (cycle 1)
{
  "cycle": 1,
  "strands": [
    {
      "title": "Migration Sequencing & Risk Prioritization",
      "content": "The 500K LOC monolith migration prioritizes extraction in four phases over 6 months, ordered by coupling simplicity and regulatory surface, not theoretical cleanness. Phase 1 (Auth, months 1-2) is lowest regulatory risk and cleanest boundary\u2014everything calls it, so extraction has immediate parallel-work value. Phase 2 (Inventory, months 2-3) is read-heavy and cache-friendly, discovering tight coupling patterns before hitting payments. Phase 3 (Payment, months 3-5) is deferred until team has learned from earlier phases; PCI-DSS scope is managed by NOT building new PCI compliance but instead keeping payment data in monolith and using tokenization (Stripe/Adyen) to scope new service outside PCI. Phase 4 (Order fulfillment, months 5-6) depends on all three and becomes the saga orchestrator. This sequence trades theoretical elegance for operational safety: it minimizes the time spent in half-migrated states and ensures each phase can run alongside the monolith without creating synchronization complexity. The strangler pattern is applied incrementally with hard cutover dates (e.g., month 4 for auth sessions) rather than open-ended parallelism.",
      "depends_on": [],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Auth should be extracted first because it has the cleanest boundaries and lowest regulatory complexity.",
          "truth": 0.85,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.03
        },
        {
          "text": "Inventory is read-heavy and should follow auth before payment extraction.",
          "truth": 0.8,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "PCI-DSS compliance should NOT drive a full rewrite of payment service; instead tokenization keeps raw card data in monolith while new service acts as orchestrator.",
          "truth": 0.82,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Order fulfillment is last because it depends on all other services and serves as cross-service orchestrator.",
          "truth": 0.88,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.02
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Technology & Architecture Decisions",
      "content": "Stack selection prioritizes operational familiarity and minimal cognitive load: Spring Boot for all three new services (leveraging existing Java expertise from the monolith), Docker containers for packaging, Kubernetes or managed infrastructure (ECS, GKE) for orchestration. Message queue is RabbitMQ (chosen over Kafka for lower operational overhead during early phases; can migrate to Kafka later if event volume demands it). Each service gets its own PostgreSQL instance or schema (dual-write strategy for data migrations, not eventual consistency without testing). Monitoring is Prometheus + Grafana (free, battle-tested, no new licensing). Service mesh (Istio) is explicitly deferred to year 2\u2014it's a distraction in month 1. Infrastructure decision prioritizes staging environment parity with production immediately; integration bugs are caught before production via staged deployment. Async patterns (sagas for payment orchestration) are introduced carefully: Phase 1-2 use synchronous calls + logging before moving to events. This trades latency for debuggability and reduced distributed transaction complexity during the learning phase.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Risk Prioritization"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Spring Boot services leverage existing Java expertise and minimize ramp-up time.",
          "truth": 0.88,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.02
        },
        {
          "text": "RabbitMQ is appropriate for Phase 1-2 async needs; Kafka migration is deferred.",
          "truth": 0.75,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.07
        },
        {
          "text": "Dual-write strategy for inventory data migration is safer than pure eventual consistency during early phases.",
          "truth": 0.79,
          "indeterminacy": 0.16,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Service mesh adoption in year 2 is correct prioritization; month 1 focus is integration, not mesh.",
          "truth": 0.82,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.04
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Team & Resource Allocation",
      "content": "A 6-person team is assigned as: 1 engineer on auth (Phases 1-2, then infrastructure/on-call), 2 engineers on inventory (Phases 2-3), 2 engineers on payment (Phases 3-5, requiring seniority + payment domain knowledge), 1 architect/tech lead on integration, saga orchestration, testing, and cross-service coordination. Resource contention is expected in month 3 when inventory finishes and payment begins\u2014this is planned, not a failure mode. Critical team mitigation: negotiate a monolith feature freeze during months 2-5 to prevent context switching and loss of capacity to legacy maintenance. Team structure assumes colocation or strong async communication (timezone considerations not discussed). Burnout risk is real; the freeze on new features is non-negotiable for success.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Risk Prioritization"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "A 1-2-2-1 team structure (auth, inventory 2x, payment 2x, architect 1) fits the 6-person constraint.",
          "truth": 0.8,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Resource contention in month 3 is predicted and manageable with planning.",
          "truth": 0.78,
          "indeterminacy": 0.17,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "A monolith feature freeze in months 2-5 is necessary to prevent capacity loss.",
          "truth": 0.83,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.05
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Risk Management & Contingency",
      "content": "Five critical risks are tracked: (1) Data consistency under dual writes and eventual consistency\u2014mitigated by synchronous calls + extensive logging in Phase 1-2, moving to events only after Phase 2 success; (2) Monolith becoming a bottleneck as all services still depend on it\u2014mitigated by anti-corruption layers and aggressive caching in each new service; (3) Payment audits and PCI compliance breaches\u2014mitigated by keeping raw card data in monolith and using third-party tokenization, not attempting full PCI certification in 6 months; (4) Scope creep (refactoring auth while extracting)\u2014mitigated by hard rule: copy-paste is acceptable, refactoring is deferred to phase 2; (5) Team burnout\u2014mitigated by feature freeze and clear completion criteria. Success metrics at month 6 are quantified: 100% auth traffic on new service with old sessions deprecated, inventory queries migrated + dual-write stopped, payment service passing integration tests (without assuming PCI scope), order service handling happy-path orchestration, all services with monitoring/alerting/runbooks, zero migration-induced production incidents. A realistic expectation is set: hitting 4 of 6 metrics constitutes success; slippage on timeline is normal and expected.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Risk Prioritization",
        "Technology & Architecture Decisions",
        "Team & Resource Allocation"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Dual-write + synchronous calls is safer than eventual consistency during Phase 1-2 learning.",
          "truth": 0.81,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "PCI compliance should NOT be attempted for new payment service in 6 months; tokenization keeps scope in monolith.",
          "truth": 0.84,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Zero migration-caused production incidents is achievable with staged rollouts and runbook preparation.",
          "truth": 0.76,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "Timeline slippage is normal; planning for buffer in month 6 is prudent.",
          "truth": 0.82,
          "indeterminacy": 0.13,
          "falsity": 0.05
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Explicit Non-Extraction & Deferred Work",
      "content": "Certain components are explicitly left in the monolith during the 6-month window: business logic that is heavily tangled (discovered during Phase 2, deferred for refactoring), user data / account management (too risky to extract alongside auth; keep with monolith during Phase 1, refactor with auth in Phase 2), reports / analytics (continue hitting monolith; no migration value in first 6 months), legacy integrations (EDI, SFTP feeds stay with monolith). This is a strategic decision to reduce scope and increase success probability. The migration is not \"everything to microservices in 6 months\" but rather \"four key services extracted in sequence, everything else refactored incrementally afterward.\" This distinction is critical for realistic planning.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Risk Prioritization"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Tangled business logic should be discovered in Phase 2 and left for post-migration refactoring.",
          "truth": 0.85,
          "indeterminacy": 0.11,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "User account data should remain in monolith during Phase 1; refactoring happens with auth in Phase 2.",
          "truth": 0.79,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "Analytics and legacy integrations have no migration priority in the 6-month window.",
          "truth": 0.87,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.03
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "declared_losses": [
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Specific discussion of how to handle schema/data model changes during inventory extraction. The answer was 'dual-write for 1 month,' but no detail on how to handle schema evolution (new columns, indexes, constraints) or whether the new service needs the entire old schema or can normalize it.",
      "shed_from": "Technology & Architecture Decisions",
      "why": "The response focused on sequencing and high-level architecture. Detailed schema migration strategy requires domain knowledge of the actual monolith data model, which is not yet known. This is deferred to Phase 1 planning.",
      "category": "context_pressure"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Discussion of API versioning, backward compatibility, and contract-driven development across services. The response assumed HTTP REST, but did not specify how breaking changes are managed when inventory API evolves during Phase 3.",
      "shed_from": "Technology & Architecture Decisions",
      "why": "Contract design is important but is secondary to getting Phase 1 right. It will emerge naturally once auth and inventory are running in production. Adding it now would over-specify and reduce adaptability.",
      "category": "practical_constraint"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Detailed security considerations beyond PCI-DSS: service-to-service authentication (mTLS, JWT, API keys), network isolation, secrets management (where are DB passwords stored?), audit logging for compliance.",
      "shed_from": "Risk Management & Contingency",
      "why": "Security is important but was not the user's primary question. The response focused on migration risk. Security best practices will be addressed in Phase 1 runbook and infrastructure design, not in high-level sequencing.",
