          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Zero migration-caused production incidents is achievable with staged rollouts and runbook preparation.",
          "truth": 0.76,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "Timeline slippage is normal; planning for buffer in month 6 is prudent.",
          "truth": 0.82,
          "indeterminacy": 0.13,
          "falsity": 0.05
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Explicit Non-Extraction & Deferred Work",
      "content": "Certain components are explicitly left in the monolith during the 6-month window: business logic that is heavily tangled (discovered during Phase 2, deferred for refactoring), user data / account management (too risky to extract alongside auth; keep with monolith during Phase 1, refactor with auth in Phase 2), reports / analytics (continue hitting monolith; no migration value in first 6 months), legacy integrations (EDI, SFTP feeds stay with monolith). This is a strategic decision to reduce scope and increase success probability. The migration is not \"everything to microservices in 6 months\" but rather \"four key services extracted in sequence, everything else refactored incrementally afterward.\" This distinction is critical for realistic planning.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Risk Prioritization"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Tangled business logic should be discovered in Phase 2 and left for post-migration refactoring.",
          "truth": 0.85,
          "indeterminacy": 0.11,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "User account data should remain in monolith during Phase 1; refactoring happens with auth in Phase 2.",
          "truth": 0.79,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "Analytics and legacy integrations have no migration priority in the 6-month window.",
          "truth": 0.87,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.03
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "declared_losses": [
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Specific discussion of how to handle schema/data model changes during inventory extraction. The answer was 'dual-write for 1 month,' but no detail on how to handle schema evolution (new columns, indexes, constraints) or whether the new service needs the entire old schema or can normalize it.",
      "shed_from": "Technology & Architecture Decisions",
      "why": "The response focused on sequencing and high-level architecture. Detailed schema migration strategy requires domain knowledge of the actual monolith data model, which is not yet known. This is deferred to Phase 1 planning.",
      "category": "context_pressure"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Discussion of API versioning, backward compatibility, and contract-driven development across services. The response assumed HTTP REST, but did not specify how breaking changes are managed when inventory API evolves during Phase 3.",
      "shed_from": "Technology & Architecture Decisions",
      "why": "Contract design is important but is secondary to getting Phase 1 right. It will emerge naturally once auth and inventory are running in production. Adding it now would over-specify and reduce adaptability.",
