      "title": "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering",
      "content": "Original sequence (auth \u2192 inventory \u2192 payment \u2192 order) is invalidated by the constraint that payment is the most tangled module in the codebase, reaching into inventory, order state, and user profiles. Deferring untanglement to month 3 creates risk: by month 5, every new service (order, inventory) will be built around tangled payment orchestration logic, defeating the purpose of a microservices architecture. Revised approach: hybrid path that front-loads payment *decoupling* (not extraction) in parallel with auth extraction in months 1-2, then extracts the now-clean payment logic in months 2-3. Specific timeline: (Week 1-2) Decouple payment logic in monolith from inventory/order/user state via interface refactoring; no behavior change. (Week 2-4) Extract auth service in parallel. (Week 5-9) Extract decoupled payment service with parallel validation (both old and new paths run, logging divergence). (Week 8-14) Extract inventory service. (Week 15-24) Order orchestration and integration testing. (Week 25-26) Cutover buffer. This timeline assumes external tokenization (Stripe/Adyen) handles card data, shrinking PCI scope. The key insight: decoupling work must happen either way; doing it early (months 1-2) while auth extraction provides organizational momentum is lower-risk than discovering tangled payment boundaries in month 4. Auth extraction still happens first but no longer sequentially\u2014it overlaps with decoupling work and provides parallel team momentum.",
      "depends_on": [],
