bio.system_prompt:
You are an experienced systems architect helping plan a migration from a monolithic application to microservices. The application handles payment processing, inventory management, user auth, and order fulfillment. The team has 6 months and limited budget. There are regulatory constraints (PCI-DSS for payments). You must balance technical debt, risk, and delivery pressure. Be specific and opinionated — this is a real migration, not a textbook exercise.

## Current tensor (cycle 3)
{
  "cycle": 3,
  "strands": [
    {
      "title": "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering",
      "content": "Original sequence (auth \u2192 inventory \u2192 payment \u2192 order) is invalidated by the constraint that payment is the most tangled module in the codebase, reaching into inventory, order state, and user profiles. Deferring untanglement to month 3 creates risk: by month 5, every new service (order, inventory) will be built around tangled payment orchestration logic, defeating the purpose of a microservices architecture. Revised approach: hybrid path that front-loads payment *decoupling* (not extraction) in parallel with auth extraction in months 1-2, then extracts the now-clean payment logic in months 2-3. Specific timeline: (Week 1-2) Decouple payment logic in monolith from inventory/order/user state via interface refactoring; no behavior change. (Week 2-4) Extract auth service in parallel. (Week 5-9) Extract decoupled payment service with parallel validation (both old and new paths run, logging divergence). (Week 8-14) Extract inventory service. (Week 15-24) Order orchestration and integration testing. (Week 25-26) Cutover buffer. This timeline assumes external tokenization (Stripe/Adyen) handles card data, shrinking PCI scope. The key insight: decoupling work must happen either way; doing it early (months 1-2) while auth extraction provides organizational momentum is lower-risk than discovering tangled payment boundaries in month 4. Auth extraction still happens first but no longer sequentially\u2014it overlaps with decoupling work and provides parallel team momentum.",
      "depends_on": [],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Payment decoupling (interface refactoring) should happen in months 1-2 in parallel with auth extraction, not after",
          "truth": 0.77,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Deferring payment extraction to month 3-5 (original plan) creates risk: new services will be built around tangled payment logic",
          "truth": 0.79,
          "indeterminacy": 0.16,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Payment logic has 30-50 tight coupling points with inventory, order, and user state (estimated from codebase description)",
          "truth": 0.68,
          "indeterminacy": 0.25,
          "falsity": 0.07
        },
        {
          "text": "Hybrid path (decouple in parallel, extract in weeks 5-9) is viable if external tokenization is adopted",
          "truth": 0.77,
          "indeterminacy": 0.18,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Decoupling via interface refactoring has zero behavioral impact and low technical risk",
          "truth": 0.84,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.04
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "PCI-DSS & Payment Risk Management",
      "content": "PCI-DSS compliance is the constraint that should *shape* extraction strategy, not block it. Original guidance ('keep monolith as PCI-scoped system, extract thin orchestrator') was conservative but created architectural debt. Revised guidance: adopt external tokenization (Stripe, Adyen, Square) such that new payment service never handles raw card data\u2014only tokens. This moves the new service *outside* PCI scope entirely. Scope shrinks, not expands. The tokenization provider (not your infrastructure) bears compliance burden. Specific implications: (1) Payment service is a stateless processor that receives tokenized card data from client/order service. (2) New service writes payment intents and authorizations to its own DB, but no raw card data crosses the boundary. (3) Audit story is clean: 'We use external tokenization; raw data never enters our systems.' (4) The decoupling work in months 1-2 specifically identifies payment orchestration logic (which can migrate) vs. card data handling (which cannot). Key assumption: team can switch from current processor to external tokenization provider contractually and operationally. If current contract locks you in or switching costs are prohibitive, the hybrid path reverts to Option A (thin orchestrator, monolith as source-of-truth). If tokenization is available, extraction becomes manageable and architecturally sound. Dual-write of payment state is now unnecessary; new service owns its authorizations and intents; monolith can be demoted to audit log only.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "External tokenization (Stripe/Adyen) is non-negotiable for keeping new payment service outside PCI scope",
          "truth": 0.91,
          "indeterminacy": 0.06,
          "falsity": 0.03
        },
        {
          "text": "With tokenization, new payment service can safely own payment intents/authorizations without PCI certification",
          "truth": 0.85,
          "indeterminacy": 0.12,
          "falsity": 0.03
        },
        {
          "text": "Audit story improves with tokenization: 'raw data never enters our systems'",
          "truth": 0.87,
          "indeterminacy": 0.09,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Without tokenization, payment service extraction in 6 months is not viable (PCI cert takes 3+ months alone)",
          "truth": 0.88,
          "indeterminacy": 0.08,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Contractual ability to switch payment processors is a hard gate for hybrid path feasibility",
          "truth": 0.86,
          "indeterminacy": 0.11,
          "falsity": 0.03
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Team Structure & Resource Allocation (Revised)",
      "content": "Original allocation (auth first sequentially, then inventory, then payment) assumed 4 phases with clear hand-offs. Hybrid path requires simultaneous work in months 1-2: one engineer on auth extraction, two engineers on payment decoupling in the monolith, one architect coordinating. This is the most resource-intensive period. Month 2-3 transition sees auth engineer move to infrastructure/staging work (Kubernetes, monitoring, CI/CD parity) while two payment engineers extract the now-decoupled logic into new service. By month 3, auth is stable, payment service is in parallel validation, and two inventory engineers begin extraction. Team burnout risk increases in month 2 because decoupling work (refactoring 30-50 coupling points) is tedious, not exciting. Mitigation: clear milestones (week 2 decoupling review, week 4 auth extraction demo, week 9 payment parallel validation sign-off) and explicit 'no new feature work' on monolith. Code freeze is still critical but the refactoring work counts as 'internal churn,' not feature development. This is a subtle communicative point: the team is refactoring the monolith's payment layer, not extracting it, which can feel safer to stakeholders. Monthly burndown meetings are essential to prevent scope creep during decoupling phase.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Simultaneous auth extraction + payment decoupling (months 1-2) requires 3-4 engineers, is most intensive period",
          "truth": 0.75,
          "indeterminacy": 0.2,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Decoupling work is low-risk but tedious; team will find it less exciting than extraction",
          "truth": 0.8,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Code freeze on new monolith features (months 2-5) is mandatory for hybrid path",
          "truth": 0.87,
          "indeterminacy": 0.1,
          "falsity": 0.03
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Technology Stack & Infrastructure Choices",
      "content": "No change from previous cycle. Spring Boot, Docker, Kubernetes (or managed), PostgreSQL per service, RabbitMQ for async. However, hybrid path increases urgency of staging environment parity: payment decoupling work (weeks 1-2) must be testable in staging before any monolith merge. This means staging environment must mirror production *before* week 1, not by end of month 1. Architect should prioritize staging setup over anything else in week 1. Payment service extraction (weeks 5-9) requires extensive integration testing against both monolith and tokenization provider; this drives tooling needs (contract testing, chaos testing, rollback simulation). These are implementation details but non-optional for payment service confidence. RabbitMQ choice is reinforced: payment service will publish events (PaymentAuthorized, PaymentFailed, PaymentCancelled) that order service will consume; this is lower-latency and simpler than request/response for orchestration.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Staging environment parity must be achieved by week 1 (not month 1 end) for decoupling validation",
          "truth": 0.82,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.04
        },
        {
          "text": "Payment service extraction requires contract testing and chaos testing (not optional)",
          "truth": 0.81,
          "indeterminacy": 0.15,
          "falsity": 0.04
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Risk Mitigation & Organizational Factors",
      "content": "Hybrid path introduces new organizational risk: team nervousness about payment systems. Original plan deferred this (safe). Hybrid plan front-loads it but frames it differently. Specific mitigation: (1) Weeks 1-2 is 'refactoring,' not 'extraction'\u2014lower perceived risk. (2) Logging divergence during parallel validation (weeks 5-9) provides empirical proof that new path is correct before cutover. (3) External tokenization reduces PCI attack surface, which is a genuine security win to sell to security team. (4) Runaway scope creep during decoupling phase is the highest risk: teams will see coupling points and want to fix the underlying design. Hard rule: document every coupling point, but only refactor to clean interfaces, no business logic changes. (5) Team burnout risk in month 2 is real (decoupling is tedious). Mitigation: celebrate small milestones weekly, not just phase completions. (6) One new risk: if tokenization provider has API changes or downtime during extraction phase, new payment service won't be testable. Mitigation: use provider's sandbox environment for weeks 5-9, only switch to live keys in week 10. Contingency: if decoupling work reveals more than 50 coupling points or if payment logic is genuinely non-deterministic (business logic bugs hidden in integration), escalate to architect in week 2. At that point, revert to Option A (thin orchestrator) and accept the architectural debt.",
      "depends_on": [
        "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering",
        "PCI-DSS & Payment Risk Management",
        "Team Structure & Resource Allocation (Revised)"
      ],
      "key_claims": [
        {
          "text": "Framing weeks 1-2 as 'refactoring' instead of 'extraction' reduces team nervousness while accomplishing decoupling",
          "truth": 0.76,
          "indeterminacy": 0.19,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Logging divergence during parallel validation (weeks 5-9) provides empirical proof, not speculation, for cutover confidence",
          "truth": 0.81,
          "indeterminacy": 0.14,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "If coupling points exceed 50 or payment logic has undocumented state dependencies, revert to thin orchestrator (Option A)",
          "truth": 0.73,
          "indeterminacy": 0.21,
          "falsity": 0.06
        },
        {
          "text": "Runaway refactoring during decoupling phase (weeks 1-2) is the #1 way this path fails",
          "truth": 0.78,
          "indeterminacy": 0.17,
          "falsity": 0.05
        },
        {
          "text": "Hybrid path's upside: by month 5, order service can call new payment service directly instead of depending on monolith orchestration",
          "truth": 0.8,
          "indeterminacy": 0.16,
          "falsity": 0.04
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "declared_losses": [
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Specific decoupling work breakdown: which 30-50 coupling points to target, in what order, and how to validate each without behavioral changes",
      "why": "Requires detailed code inspection of payment module. Decoupling strategy is stated at conceptual level (interface refactoring) but not itemized. Would need repository access or codebase walkthrough.",
      "shed_from": "Migration Sequencing & Phase Ordering",
      "category": "context_pressure"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Switching costs to external tokenization provider: contract analysis, integration effort, risk of current processor lock-in, PCI compliance status with current processor",
      "why": "These are deal-breakers for the hybrid path but cannot be assessed without knowing current processor (Stripe already, or legacy payment gateway?). Deferred pending user response.",
      "shed_from": "PCI-DSS & Payment Risk Management",
      "category": "context_pressure"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Detailed week-by-week breakdown of decoupling work (milestones, PR reviews, testing strategy for refactoring)",
      "why": "Provided month-by-month and week-by-week phase breakdown, but not task-level detail within weeks 1-2. That belongs in a 1-pager project plan, not migration strategy document.",
      "shed_from": "Team Structure & Resource Allocation (Revised)",
      "category": "authorial_choice"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Comparison to Option B (aggressive immediate extraction) with detailed cost analysis",
      "why": "Hybrid path is recommended over Option B, but only sketched why Option B is riskier (requires senior payment engineer, tighter timeline). Did not detail what would have to go right for Option B to be viable.",
      "shed_from": "Risk Mitigation & Organizational Factors",
      "category": "traversal_bias"
    },
    {
      "what_was_lost": "Details on how to communicate 'revert to Option A' if decoupling reveals >50 coupling points; organizational decision-making for escalation",
      "why": "Escalation trigger is identified but not the decision-making process or stakeholder communication strategy if hybrid path becomes infeasible midway.",
      "shed_from": "Risk Mitigation & Organizational Factors",
      "category": "practical_constraint"
    }
  ],
  "open_questions": [
    "What is the current payment processor (Stripe, legacy gateway, in-house), and is switching contractually feasible within 6 months?",
    "Does the team have a senior engineer (or access to a consultant) who has executed PCI-compliant payment extraction before? This determines confidence in the hybrid path.",
    "How many tight coupling points exist between payment logic and inventory/order/user state? (Ballpark: 20? 50? 100+?) This determines if decoupling work is weeks or months.",
    "Is the monolith's payment logic stateful, or is it mostly stateless orchestration? Stateful logic hidden in integration is a major decoupling risk.",
    "What is the team's current familiarity with external tokenization APIs (Stripe, Adyen)? Will this be a learning curve in week 5?",
    "Does your current PCI audit roadmap include deadlines or scheduled audit dates? This changes risk tolerance.",
    "What is the budget for switching payment processors or adopting external tokenization (processor fees, integration work)?",
    "Can you run both old and new payment paths in parallel during weeks 5-9 without race conditions or data consistency issues? (Or will you need a feature flag per transaction?)",
    "How do you currently handle payment retries and idempotency in the monolith? This logic must survive extraction unchanged.",
    "Is there a tech lead or architect on the team currently, or will this be a gap?"
  ],
  "instructions_for_next": "Expect next conversation to focus on feasibility gates for the hybrid path. Immediate follow-ups in priority order: (1) current payment processor + contractual flexibility (5 min); (2) coupling point estimation via quick code review or team estimate (10 min); (3) senior payment engineering availability on team or budget for external help (5 min). If all three are positive, hybrid path is green-lit. If any is negative, conversation shifts to refining Option A (thin orchestrator) or scaling back scope. Second-priority topics: (a) current PCI audit status and deadlines, which sets compliance urgency; (b) statefulnes of payment logic, which determines decoupling complexity; (c) team composition and whether tech lead capacity exists for architectural coordination. Third-priority: detailed week-by-week breakdown of decoupling work, which becomes a project plan once feasibility is confirmed. If hybrid path is deemed infeasible, shift focus to refining Option A with explicit acknowledgment that the result will be a strangler pattern dependent on monolith orchestration through year 2, with clear articulation of what that means for inventory and order service design constraints."
}

